<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="189" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" type="key">
<paragraph blockId="1.[174,1233,1706,1843]" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
<keyLead pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
<keyStep pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
<key pageId="1" pageNumber="188">
1 (2). Smaller species: 
<quantity box="[409,527,1706,1728]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.7" metricValueMax="4.3" metricValueMin="3.1" pageId="1" pageNumber="188" unit="mm" value="3.7" valueMax="4.3" valueMin="3.1">3.1–4.3 mm</quantity>
. Elytral intervals 3 with 1 setiferous puncture behind middle only. Head large and wide, at 0.87–0.94 times as wide as pronotum. Posterior angles of pronotum almost obtused, rounded on apex (
<figureCitation box="[432,481,1764,1786]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[170,203,704,726]" captionTargetBox="[208,1165,178,650]" captionTargetId="figure-476@2.[193,1205,166,676]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1–3. Head and pronotum of Anthracus (after Jaeger, 2011): 1 — A. londicornis; 2 — A. transversalis; 3 — A. consputus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452326" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452326/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="188">fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Antennae very long, at 3.2–3.6 times as long as pronotum. Striae of elytra delicate. Head brown, mouthparts reddish or yellow-brown; pronotum (except lighter narrow lateral margin) dark brown or reddish brown, sometimes with indistinct dark macula on the disk. Elytra with
</key>
</keyStep>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[170,874,656,678]" lastBlockId="2.[166,1231,853,1508]" pageId="2" pageNumber="189">
